      "description": "# Gmail Email Ingestion via Google Pub/Sub & Apps Script\n\nHere's the full spec rewritten for Gmail, using **Google Pub/Sub push subscriptions** (Gmail's native webhook mechanism) as the backbone instead of Power Automate.\n\n---\n\n## How Gmail \"Webhooks\" Actually Work\n\nGmail doesn't support direct webhooks, but Google provides an official push notification system:\n\n1. **Gmail Watch API** — tells Gmail to monitor an inbox and publish notifications to a Google Pub/Sub topic when new messages arrive\n2. **Google Pub/Sub** — receives those notifications and immediately pushes them to your HTTPS endpoint\n3. **Your backend** — receives the Pub/Sub push, uses the Gmail API to fetch the actual email content, and ingests it\n\nThis is the production-grade approach used by enterprise Gmail integrations. Alternatively, for tenants who prefer a no-code setup, **Google Apps Script** can poll Gmail and POST to your webhook on a time trigger — this is simpler but introduces up to a 1-minute delay.\n\n---\n\n## Webhook Endpoint\n\n**Primary endpoint (Pub/Sub push):**\n```\nPOST /webhooks/email/gmail/:tenantId\n```\n\n**Authentication:** Pub/Sub push requests include a Bearer token in the `Authorization` header issued by Google. Verify this token against Google's token info endpoint (`https://oauth2.googleapis.com/tokeninfo`) to confirm it's a legitimate Pub/Sub push and that the `email` claim matches your registered service account. Additionally, validate a `?token=<secret>` query parameter appended to the subscription push URL during setup as a secondary layer.\n\n**What Pub/Sub delivers:** The push payload is a Pub/Sub message envelope — not the email itself. The `data` field is base64-encoded and contains only the Gmail `historyId` and the user's email address. Your backend must then call the Gmail API to retrieve the actual message.\n\n**Ingestion flow:**\n\n```\nPub/Sub Push → Your endpoint → Decode historyId → Gmail API (history.list) \n→ Gmail